WEBVTT

1
00:00.570 --> 00:04.050
- Welcome to Understanding
Quantum Information and Computation.

2
00:04.050 --> 00:09.300
My name is John Watrous, and I'm the technical director
of IBM Quantum Education.

3
00:09.300 --> 00:16.710
The purpose of this series is to provide you with
a solid understanding of quantum information and computation, and that means getting
into the technical details

4
00:16.710 --> 00:24.030
of quantum information and seeing how quantum
computing really works, what it can do and what it can't do.

5
00:24.030 --> 00:29.130
If you haven't already
watched the overview video for this series, I encourage you to check that out.

6
00:29.130 --> 00:38.550
In that video, you'll find information about what sort of background
preparation is recommended for this series, as well as an outline of
the topics to be covered.

7
00:38.550 --> 00:44.580
Also, be sure to check
out the Qiskit textbook, which covers the same
material as this video series in a written form,

8
00:44.580 --> 00:51.000
and it also includes
interactive components and interfaces to hardware and software designed to help you to better understand

9
00:51.000 --> 00:58.770
quantum information and computation. You'll find links to the overview video and the Qiskit textbook
in the description.

10
00:58.770 --> 01:02.430
This is lesson one of
unit one of the series.

11
01:02.430 --> 01:09.150
Unit one covers the basics
of quantum information, and in the first lesson of this unit, we'll focus on how
quantum information works

12
01:09.150 --> 01:16.200
for single systems, meaning that we have
just one physical system or a device of some sort that
stores quantum information

13
01:16.200 --> 01:20.940
and we're considering how that
one system or device works in isolation.

14
01:20.940 --> 01:27.720
In the lesson following this one, we'll discuss how
quantum information works when we have multiple systems and that will allow us

15
01:27.720 --> 01:34.980
to describe interesting
and important concepts such as quantum algorithms that make use of multiple qubits

16
01:34.980 --> 01:43.080
and quantum protocols
involving multiple individuals that process quantum information and transmit it back and
forth to one another.

17
01:43.080 --> 01:50.880
But before getting into those discussions, it makes sense to start with the
comparatively simple setting of a single system in isolation,

18
01:50.880 --> 01:57.270
partly because it's good to start simple, but also because as we will see, the description of how
quantum information works

19
01:57.270 --> 02:04.020
for single systems in isolation leads very naturally and logically to the description of how
quantum information works

20
02:04.020 --> 02:07.470
for multiple systems.

21
02:07.470 --> 02:10.980
Here's a brief overview of the lesson.

22
02:10.980 --> 02:14.640
We're gonna start by discussing
classical information.

23
02:14.640 --> 02:22.050
Now, the purpose of this lesson is not to explain how
classical information works, it's to explain how
quantum information works,

24
02:22.050 --> 02:30.660
but to explain how
quantum information works, it's very helpful to begin
with classical information and to use it as a
familiar point of reference

25
02:30.660 --> 02:33.750
when we discuss quantum information.

26
02:33.750 --> 02:42.510
At a mathematical level, quantum and classical information actually have pretty similar descriptions with some key differences, of course.

27
02:42.510 --> 02:47.190
In fact, quantum information
really isn't separate from classical information at all.

28
02:47.190 --> 02:50.850
It's an extension of
classical information.

29
02:50.850 --> 02:58.500
The fact of the matter
is, at least in my view, that you really can't
understand quantum information if you don't understand
classical information,

30
02:58.500 --> 03:02.940
so starting with classical
information makes sense.

31
03:02.940 --> 03:10.710
I do expect that this
content will be familiar to some viewers, but even if you are familiar with it, I don't recommend that you skip it.

32
03:10.710 --> 03:19.170
In addition to highlighting the aspects of classical information that are most relevant to
understanding quantum information, we're gonna introduce the
Dirac notation in this part,

33
03:19.170 --> 03:25.470
which is a standard way
that we're gonna use to describe vectors and
matrices throughout the series.

34
03:25.470 --> 03:30.420
As it turns out, the Dirac notation isn't
specific to quantum information.

35
03:30.420 --> 03:39.360
It can equally well be used in the context of classical information as well as many other settings where vectors and matrices arise.

36
03:39.360 --> 03:47.190
We'll then move on to quantum information, and specifically, we'll
discuss the representation of quantum states as vectors,

37
03:47.190 --> 03:56.880
a simple type of measurement called a standard basis measurement, and unitary operations, which describe discreet time
changes in quantum systems.

38
03:56.880 --> 04:02.430
Again, all in the setting
of single systems.

39
04:02.430 --> 04:08.430
Before we get started with lesson itself, it will be helpful to clarify that there are actually two descriptions

40
04:08.430 --> 04:14.550
of quantum information, the simplified description, which is what we'll be
focusing on in this lesson

41
04:14.550 --> 04:23.880
and throughout this first unit and the general description, which is covered in a later unit, specifically in the
third unit of the series.

42
04:23.880 --> 04:29.430
The simplified description,
true to its name, is simpler and it's
typically learned first.

43
04:29.430 --> 04:38.490
In the simplified description, as I've already suggested, quantum states are represented by vectors and operations are represented
by unitary matrices.

44
04:38.490 --> 04:44.700
This description of quantum
information is sufficient for an understanding of
most quantum algorithms, for instance,

45
04:44.700 --> 04:48.600
so it isn't oversimplified, it's the real thing.

46
04:48.600 --> 04:55.140
However, as we will
discover as we go along, it does have some limitations.

47
04:55.140 --> 05:03.270
For instance, if we wanna
model the effects of noise on quantum systems, this description turns out to be lacking.

48
05:03.270 --> 05:11.640
The general description, on
the other hand, is more general and ultimately, it's more
powerful in a mathematical sense.

49
05:11.640 --> 05:18.720
In this description, quantum states are represented by a special class of matrices
called density matrices,

50
05:18.720 --> 05:25.830
and more general class of
measurements and operations can be described including
noise, for instance.

51
05:25.830 --> 05:32.280
It's entirely consistent with
the simplified description and in fact, you can essentially view
the simplified description

52
05:32.280 --> 05:39.330
as a special case of
the general description, and it also includes classical information as a special case.

53
05:39.330 --> 05:46.020
It's also really quite
beautiful in how it all works, so I strongly encourage you to learn about this general description

54
05:46.020 --> 05:53.220
when the time is right, but the simplified description is the more natural place to start, and so that is what we will do.

55
05:53.220 --> 06:01.770
We're going to begin by talking about classical information with an eye on the aspects
of classical information that are most relevant
to quantum information

56
06:01.770 --> 06:06.060
and the way that it's
described mathematically.

57
06:06.060 --> 06:12.330
Imagine that we have a
physical system or a device of some sort that stores information.

58
06:12.330 --> 06:16.800
We're gonna give this system the name X, but there's nothing
important about this name.

59
06:16.800 --> 06:24.180
We could use any other
name if we preferred, but just to pick a name,
we're gonna call the system X.

60
06:24.180 --> 06:33.120
We're gonna make an assumption about X, which is that there is a
finite set of classical states that X can possibly be
in at any given moment.

61
06:33.120 --> 06:41.100
Here, when I refer to a classical state, I mean a configuration of the system that can be recognized and
described unambiguously

62
06:41.100 --> 06:44.520
without any uncertainty or error.

63
06:44.520 --> 06:51.420
Really, this is something that you can think about intuitively. At a mathematical level, we simply define the
set of classical states,

64
06:51.420 --> 06:58.560
we choose it however we want to or in whatever way best
describes the device that we're working with.

65
06:58.560 --> 07:07.050
Let us give the name sigma to
this set of classical states, and again, let me emphasize
that we're assuming that sigma is a finite set.

66
07:07.050 --> 07:12.570
The set of classical
states of this system X is not infinitely large like
the set of all natural numbers.

67
07:12.570 --> 07:17.850
It's finite, and that's just an
assumption that we're making.

68
07:17.850 --> 07:27.540
For example, it could be that X is a bit, in which case, the classical state set is the set containing two
elements: zero and one.

69
07:27.540 --> 07:32.070
Sometimes we refer to this
set as the binary alphabet.

70
07:32.070 --> 07:40.470
Another example is that X is
an ordinary six-sided die, in which case, the classical states are the numbers one through six.

71
07:40.470 --> 07:43.500
Of course, we're talking
about an abstraction here.

72
07:43.500 --> 07:50.040
An actual six-sided die may
have many different attributes such as its precise
position, its orientation,

73
07:50.040 --> 07:58.200
its temperature, and so on. But with respect to the information that's most typically relevant when we're talking about a six-sided die,

74
07:58.200 --> 08:07.140
the classical states are
the numbers one through six indicated by the number of dots on whichever side of the die is facing up.

75
08:07.140 --> 08:14.250
If X is a switch on a
standard sort of electric fan that you might have in your home, then perhaps the classical states

76
08:14.250 --> 08:18.900
are the settings high,
medium, low and off.

77
08:18.900 --> 08:25.830
These are just examples. We could imagine systems having different classical
state sets than these, but hopefully, they convey the idea

78
08:25.830 --> 08:34.620
that this notion of a classical state is something that should be
familiar and can be understood in simple and intuitive terms.

79
08:34.620 --> 08:41.190
Mathematically speaking, the set of classical states
is just a finite set, and of course, this set must
also be non empty as well.

80
08:41.190 --> 08:47.490
There has to be at least
one classical state that the system can be in and there has to be at
least two classical states

81
08:47.490 --> 08:53.190
if the system is going to be useful at all for storing information.

82
08:53.190 --> 08:59.610
Now, in some situations, we might know that X is
in some particular state, but in many situations,

83
08:59.610 --> 09:07.140
that arise in the setting
of information processing, there may be uncertainty about the classical state of a
system at a particular moment

84
09:07.140 --> 09:12.600
so that each possible classical state has some probability associated with it.

85
09:12.600 --> 09:19.140
For example, if X is a bit, then perhaps it's the case that X is in the classical state zero

86
09:19.140 --> 09:25.830
with probability three quarters and it's in the state one
with probability one quarter.

87
09:25.830 --> 09:32.580
We're going to refer to this
as a probabilistic state, and we could express
this probabilistic state, as you see right here,

88
09:32.580 --> 09:38.580
simply by indicating what
the probabilities are for the different classical states.

89
09:38.580 --> 09:47.910
A more succinct way to express
this probabilistic state is by a vector, specifically the representation
that you see right here

90
09:47.910 --> 09:55.380
is a column vector, and this vector indicates
what the probabilities are for the two possible classical states.

91
09:55.380 --> 10:03.960
To be more specific, the first entry indicates
what the probability is for X to be in the state zero, and the second entry tells
us what the probability is

92
10:03.960 --> 10:10.350
for the system to be in the state one. This is simply the natural way to order the binary alphabet,

93
10:10.350 --> 10:16.890
or at least, it's the way that
we are trained to do this. With zero first and one second.

94
10:16.890 --> 10:22.500
Going forward, we're gonna use
the term probability vector to indicate a vector like this.

95
10:22.500 --> 10:29.640
Specifically, it's a vector whose entries are all
non-negative real numbers and where the sum of the
entries is equal to one,

96
10:29.640 --> 10:34.890
so it makes sense to
think about these entries as being probabilities.

97
10:34.890 --> 10:41.310
Here in this example, there are just two entries because there's just two
classical states of the system we're talking about,

98
10:41.310 --> 10:47.730
but in general, there could
be any number of entries with the understanding
being that there's one entry for each classical state

99
10:47.730 --> 10:52.110
of whatever system we're talking about.

100
10:52.110 --> 10:59.700
We're going to continue
discussing classical information, probability vectors and
so on in just a moment, but first, it's gonna be really helpful

101
10:59.700 --> 11:05.040
to introduce some notation
for describing vectors known as the Dirac notation.

102
11:05.040 --> 11:08.760
In fact, this is just the first
part of the Dirac notation.

103
11:08.760 --> 11:15.120
There are a couple of other
aspects of the Dirac notation that we'll see a little
bit later in the lesson.

104
11:15.120 --> 11:22.890
This notation is gonna be
quite central to the way that we describe quantum information, so it's essential to
understand how it works,

105
11:22.890 --> 11:29.160
but fortunately, it's very simple and it really doesn't have
anything specifically to do with quantum information,

106
11:29.160 --> 11:35.130
so we can introduce it now
in the familiar context of classical information.

107
11:35.130 --> 11:41.423
As before, we assume that we have a set sigma of
classical states of some system, and let's assume

108
11:41.423 --> 11:47.490
that we have an ordering
of these classical states, just like how we refer to an
ordering of the binary alphabet

109
11:47.490 --> 11:55.740
in the previous example. Another way of saying this
is that the elements of sigma are placed in correspondence
with the integer

110
11:55.740 --> 12:03.000
from one to however many
elements are contained in sigma, which is what this notation right here with two bars around sigma means.

111
12:03.000 --> 12:06.210
That's the number of
elements in the set sigma.

112
12:06.210 --> 12:11.340
So there's a first state,
a second state, and so on.

113
12:11.340 --> 12:17.310
The specific ordering or
correspondence that we choose isn't actually gonna matter all that much.

114
12:17.310 --> 12:23.130
What's really important is
that we have an ordering and we stick to it.

115
12:23.130 --> 12:29.520
For many classical state
sets that we'll encounter, there will be a standard ordering just like we have with
the binary alphabet,

116
12:29.520 --> 12:33.540
and if there isn't a standard ordering, we can just choose one.

117
12:33.540 --> 12:40.020
But whatever it is, the understanding is that we stick to it.

118
12:40.020 --> 12:43.620
Now, here's the notation
that's being introduced.

119
12:43.620 --> 12:53.130
For any choice of a classical
state a from our set sigma, we write this right here, which is read as ket a
to mean the column vector

120
12:53.130 --> 13:00.240
that has a one in entry corresponding to a and a zero for all other entries.

121
13:00.240 --> 13:06.900
For example, if we return
to the binary alphabet, which, as you might have guessed, is a very important example

122
13:06.900 --> 13:14.880
that we'll return to again and again. Then ket zero and ket one are the vectors that are defined right here.

123
13:14.880 --> 13:22.080
Ket zero is the vector
that has a one in the entry corresponding to the classical state zero, which is the first entry,

124
13:22.080 --> 13:27.420
and a zero for all other entries, and in this case, there's
only one other entry.

125
13:27.420 --> 13:34.020
Similarly, ket one is
this vector right here where we have a one in the
entry corresponding to one,

126
13:34.020 --> 13:41.880
which is the second entry, and a zero for all other entries, which, again, is just one entry.

127
13:41.880 --> 13:48.510
Here's another example. In this example, we have a
classical state set sigma corresponding to the four suits

128
13:48.510 --> 13:54.720
in a standard deck of playing cards: clubs, diamonds, hearts, and spades.

129
13:54.720 --> 13:59.550
In this case, there really isn't a
universally agreed upon ordering of these suits.

130
13:59.550 --> 14:07.920
For many card games, there is no ordering at all. They're just four different suits and that's all that matters, and there are different card
games that do order these suits

131
14:07.920 --> 14:11.100
in different ways, but it doesn't really matter.

132
14:11.100 --> 14:15.390
We can just choose an
ordering like the one that you see right here.

133
14:15.390 --> 14:22.230
This happens to be alphabetical ordering according to the names of these four suits written in English,

134
14:22.230 --> 14:31.050
Assuming that we've picked
this particular ordering, then we define these four vectors: ket clubs, ket diamonds,
ket hearts, and ket spades

135
14:31.050 --> 14:38.430
as you see right here, and these vectors correspond
to the general description that you see up here.

136
14:38.430 --> 14:43.200
Given that we've chosen
this particular ordering for these four suits.

137
14:43.200 --> 14:46.320
We can do the same thing for any classical state
set that we choose.

138
14:46.320 --> 14:52.830
Keeping in mind that classical
state set always means finite and non empty set.

139
14:52.830 --> 15:01.650
Vectors of this form are
called standard basis vectors, and it's a very basic fact about vectors that every vector can be
expressed in a unique way

140
15:01.650 --> 15:05.700
as a linear combination
of standard basis vectors.

141
15:05.700 --> 15:13.200
For instance, going back to the example from just a moment ago, the probability vector
we saw can be expressed

142
15:13.200 --> 15:19.410
as you see right here. It's basically just an alternative way of expressing vectors

143
15:19.410 --> 15:23.250
that's gonna be very handy for several reasons going forward.

144
15:23.250 --> 15:31.650
And with that notation now in our hands, let's return to the discussion
of classical information and probabilistic states, in particular.

145
15:31.650 --> 15:38.490
And let's consider what happens
when we measure a system while it's in some probabilistic state.

146
15:38.490 --> 15:45.750
We might not ordinarily
refer to a measurement or the act of measuring
something in a classical setting, but the term makes sense.

147
15:45.750 --> 15:55.230
In essence, when we talk
about measuring the system X in this context, we just mean that we look at it and we recognize whatever state it's in.

148
15:55.230 --> 16:02.130
Of course, when we look at the system, we don't see a probabilistic state, we see a classical state,

149
16:02.130 --> 16:08.970
and the particular
classical state that we see is one that we can
imagine is chosen randomly according to the probabilities.

150
16:08.970 --> 16:16.200
Now, you might object on
philosophical grounds to the idea that the classical state we see is somehow chosen at random

151
16:16.200 --> 16:23.490
at the moment that we measure or we look at the system, the system simply was in some particular
classical state all along

152
16:23.490 --> 16:31.140
and we just happen to have
learned what the state was, but for the sake of thinking about the mathematical
framework we're working with,

153
16:31.140 --> 16:39.300
it's okay to think about it this way and doing so will allow us to draw a parallel with
quantum information a little bit later.

154
16:39.300 --> 16:46.860
Let's suppose that the
classical state that we see is the classical state a, which could be any state in our set sigma.

155
16:46.860 --> 16:52.680
This changes the probabilistic
state of X in general, at least from our point of view.

156
16:52.680 --> 16:58.440
The probabilities no longer
have any significance because we now know what
the classical state of X is.

157
16:58.440 --> 17:03.060
It's a, and there's no longer
any uncertainty about this.

158
17:03.060 --> 17:10.410
So we would now say this
that the probability that the system is in the state a is one.

159
17:10.410 --> 17:18.990
We know this because we just looked at it and we saw that the classical state is a, so the new probabilistic state of X is one

160
17:18.990 --> 17:24.690
in which the probability of
being in the classical state a is equal to one.

161
17:24.690 --> 17:29.790
And that probabilistic state is represented by the
probability vector ket a.

162
17:29.790 --> 17:36.120
We have a one in the entry corresponding to the classical state a and a zero in all other entries.

163
17:36.120 --> 17:43.920
For example, if we again
consider the situation where X is a bit and we have the same
probabilistic state as before,

164
17:43.920 --> 17:50.310
then if we measure X, we can imagine that a
transition takes place.

165
17:50.310 --> 17:59.490
With probability three quarters, we see the classical state zero, and by measuring, we transition to ket zero
being our probabilistic state,

166
17:59.490 --> 18:04.440
and with probability one quarter, we transition to ket one.

167
18:04.440 --> 18:10.800
You can think about this as a transition of knowledge if you prefer as opposed to an actual
physical transition,

168
18:10.800 --> 18:16.230
but what's important for
the sake of this lesson is to recognize how the mathematics works.

169
18:16.230 --> 18:22.350
It's kind of trivial actually, but by recognizing this triviality, the analogous description
for the quantum setting

170
18:22.350 --> 18:26.400
might seem a little bit less mysterious.

171
18:26.400 --> 18:33.180
One final note is that to another person who didn't happen to see what
the classical state of X was when we measured it,

172
18:33.180 --> 18:38.820
the probabilistic state
naturally wouldn't change as a result of us having measured it.

173
18:38.820 --> 18:46.680
That's okay. Different individuals can
have different knowledge of a particular system and correspondingly choose
different probabilistic states

174
18:46.680 --> 18:50.310
to represent their
knowledge of that system.

175
18:50.310 --> 18:57.900
In the last part of this discussion of classical information, we'll talk about classical operations that can be performed on a system,

176
18:57.900 --> 19:01.680
starting with deterministic operations.

177
19:01.680 --> 19:09.390
When we perform an operation on a system, its state generally changes as a result, and in this context, the word deterministic means

178
19:09.390 --> 19:15.900
that the result of performing
the operation depends entirely on whatever classical
state the system was in

179
19:15.900 --> 19:19.680
prior to the operation being performed.

180
19:19.680 --> 19:28.830
In other words, there's
no element of chance when a deterministic
operation is performed, so there's no randomness
or uncertainty involved.

181
19:28.830 --> 19:34.080
In mathematical terms, deterministic operations
are described by functions.

182
19:34.080 --> 19:40.950
Every function f of the form
that you see right here, which means that both the input and the output of the function

183
19:40.950 --> 19:46.890
correspond to elements of
our classical state set sigma describes a deterministic operation.

184
19:46.890 --> 19:53.280
The classical state a is
transformed into the state f of a for each choice of a state a.

185
19:53.280 --> 20:00.777
For every function f of this form, there will always be a unique matrix M satisfying this condition
that you see right here,

186
20:00.777 --> 20:08.040
and that is that by multiplying
M to the vector ket a gives us the vector ket f of a,

187
20:08.040 --> 20:11.640
and that's true for every
choice of a classical state a.

188
20:11.640 --> 20:17.550
It's not too hard to write down
an explicit description of M given whatever function f
of this form we've chosen.

189
20:17.550 --> 20:22.890
It will always have exactly
one, one in each column with every other entry equal to zero.

190
20:22.890 --> 20:30.360
And here's the formula. The b, a entry of M is equal to one if b is equal to f of a

191
20:30.360 --> 20:37.950
and otherwise, it's equal to zero, and by this, we mean
this is the entry of M whose row corresponds to b

192
20:37.950 --> 20:41.430
and whose column corresponds to a.

193
20:41.430 --> 20:46.950
We'll see a few examples in just a moment, and we'll see why this formula works.

194
20:46.950 --> 20:53.490
Now, it might not be clear why we would want to take a function and express it as a matrix like this,

195
20:53.490 --> 21:01.650
but it does make sense to do this. One of the reasons, and perhaps, it's the main reason, is that if we have a system
in a probabilistic state

196
21:01.650 --> 21:08.010
and we perform a deterministic
operation on that system, then the resulting probabilistic
state can be obtained

197
21:08.010 --> 21:14.400
by matrix-vector multiplication, i.e., if our system is
in a probabilistic state

198
21:14.400 --> 21:20.850
that's represented by
some probability vector v and we perform the deterministic
operation described by M

199
21:20.850 --> 21:27.120
on that system, then the resulting probabilistic state will be given by M times v.

200
21:27.120 --> 21:35.370
Here, by the way, this arrow with a little
bar on it like this is just a common notation in mathematics for indicating how one
thing gets mapped to

201
21:35.370 --> 21:41.760
or transformed into another thing. You could just use an ordinary arrow, but this is conventional

202
21:41.760 --> 21:49.140
and it's recognizable and maybe it's a little bit more specific than just an arrow, which could mean many different things.

203
21:49.140 --> 21:53.640
Now let's take a look at an example or a collection of examples, really.

204
21:53.640 --> 22:00.420
Let's consider what happens when we take our classical state set sigma to be once again the binary alphabet.

205
22:00.420 --> 22:08.760
There aren't too many different functions of the form we've been discussing when this is our classical state set and to be more precise, there are just four
functions of this form.

206
22:08.760 --> 22:13.320
Here, those four functions are described by their so-called tables of values.

207
22:13.320 --> 22:18.930
The first table describes
the first function, which we've named f1.

208
22:18.930 --> 22:27.377
For each possible input on the left, we list the corresponding
output on the right, so f1 of zero is equal to zero,

209
22:27.377 --> 22:34.350
and f1 of one is, again, equal to zero, and that is to say that f1 is
the constant zero function.

210
22:34.350 --> 22:37.830
It always takes the value zero.

211
22:37.830 --> 22:41.370
The second function f2
is the identity function.

212
22:41.370 --> 22:47.040
The output is always equal to the input as you can see from the second table.

213
22:47.040 --> 22:50.640
The third function f3 is
described by the third table.

214
22:50.640 --> 22:55.560
f3 of zero is equal to one, and f3 of one is equal to zero.

215
22:55.560 --> 23:01.230
This function is better
known as the not function or logical negation.

216
23:01.230 --> 23:07.740
We sometimes also call it a bit flip because it flips zero
to one and one to zero.

217
23:07.740 --> 23:14.310
The last function f4 is,
again, a constant function just like the first one, but this one is the constant one function

218
23:14.310 --> 23:17.520
because it always takes the value one.

219
23:17.520 --> 23:22.470
And those are the only four functions from the binary alphabet to itself.

220
23:22.470 --> 23:28.860
Here are the four matrices that correspond to these four functions that are described by
the formula from before,

221
23:28.860 --> 23:35.340
which you can see right here, and if you're so inclined, you can pause the video and check this.

222
23:35.340 --> 23:41.880
Just remember that with matrices, the order of the indices is always rows first, column second.

223
23:41.880 --> 23:50.130
So the b, a entry corresponds
to row b and column a or the row that corresponds
to the classical state b

224
23:50.130 --> 23:54.270
and the column that corresponds
to the classical state a.

225
23:54.270 --> 24:01.890
So for example, if we look
at the first function, we have the f1 of zero is equal to zero

226
24:01.890 --> 24:06.990
and correspondingly, the
zero, zero entry of M1 is equal to one.

227
24:06.990 --> 24:14.430
Well, the one, zero
entry which is right here is equal to zero, and you can do the same thing for the case

228
24:14.430 --> 24:19.350
where the input is equal to one and similarly, for the
other three functions.

229
24:19.350 --> 24:28.410
You can also check that this
formula from before is true and you can just go one by one through all the different
possibilities to verify this.

230
24:28.410 --> 24:35.730
And in fact, if you think about the way that
matrix multiplication works, really you can just kind of eyeball this.

231
24:35.730 --> 24:43.290
When you multiply a matrix to a standard basis factor like this, you can imagine that
you're taking the input

232
24:43.290 --> 24:49.530
and dropping it into the
top of one of the matrices in whichever column corresponds
to the classical state

233
24:49.530 --> 24:56.250
inside of the ket, and the output that you
get is simply that column as a probability vector.

234
24:56.250 --> 25:02.670
So for example, M3 multiplied to ket
zero gives you zero, one

235
25:02.670 --> 25:06.240
as a probability vector, which is ket one.

236
25:06.240 --> 25:13.200
M3 multiplied to ket
one gives you one, zero, which is ket zero and so on.

237
25:13.200 --> 25:21.120
We'll discuss operations on
probabilistic states more in just a moment, but first, let's introduce the second part of the Dirac notation.

238
25:21.120 --> 25:27.750
This is gonna be helpful
for talking about operations and thinking about them as major Cs, and it's also gonna be a standard tool

239
25:27.750 --> 25:32.700
that we'll continue to use going forward. The setup is just like it was before.

240
25:32.700 --> 25:40.200
We have whatever classical state set sigma that we're working with and we assume that we have some way of
ordering those classical states.

241
25:40.200 --> 25:49.200
We then write this thing
that you see right here where this time the
angled bar is on the left rather than the right to mean
the row vector having a one

242
25:49.200 --> 25:56.190
in the entry that
corresponds to a and a zero for all of the other entries corresponding to all the
other classical states.

243
25:56.190 --> 26:03.360
So the difference between
this thing and ket a is that this is a row vector and
ket a is a column vector,

244
26:03.360 --> 26:07.290
but otherwise, the vectors
are defined in a similar way.

245
26:07.290 --> 26:14.190
We read this as bra a, I'm not sure if that's
supposed to be funny, but the idea is that the names bra and ket

246
26:14.190 --> 26:19.440
are two halves of the word bracket, and we'll have more to say
about that in just a moment.

247
26:19.440 --> 26:23.310
But first, let's take a look
at a very quick example.

248
26:23.310 --> 26:29.850
For the binary alphabet, we have that bra zero is
this row vector right here analogous to ket a,

249
26:29.850 --> 26:37.110
except it's a row vector
instead of a column vector and bra one is this vector right here.

250
26:37.110 --> 26:43.860
Now in general, if we multiply a row
vector to a column vector, just thinking about these as matrices

251
26:43.860 --> 26:52.680
that happen to have just
one row or just one column, then we get a one by one matrix, which we can think
about as being a scaler.

252
26:52.680 --> 26:59.370
Here, by the way, you should
think about these stars as representing arbitrary numbers.

253
26:59.370 --> 27:05.610
In particular, if we
multiply the row vector bra a to the column vector ket b,

254
27:05.610 --> 27:09.960
then there are two things that can happen.

255
27:09.960 --> 27:16.410
One is that a and b are equal, so they're the same classical state, in which case, the ones will line up

256
27:16.410 --> 27:25.440
and the product will be equal to one or it could be the case
the a and b are different,

257
27:25.440 --> 27:30.630
and so the ones don't line up and the product is equal to zero.

258
27:30.630 --> 27:35.760
A simple way of expressing
these observations is like this right here.

259
27:35.760 --> 27:45.540
And just to keep things tidy, we write this product like this with just one bar in the middle and it means exactly the same
thing as this right here.

260
27:45.540 --> 27:52.740
And now you can see how the
bra and the ket go together to form a bracket, which is
also called an inner product,

261
27:52.740 --> 27:57.930
and that's something
that's quite important that we'll come back to
in lesson number three.

262
27:57.930 --> 28:05.580
Multiplying a column
vector to a row vector, on the other hand, gives us a matrix as you can see right here.

263
28:05.580 --> 28:12.810
So for example, going back yet
again to the binary alphabet, if we multiply ket zero to bra zero,

264
28:12.810 --> 28:20.760
what we get is this matrix right here, and we can go through
the other possibilities to see what happens.

265
28:20.760 --> 28:27.930
Ket zero times bra one gives
us this matrix right here where the one has now moved
over to this position.

266
28:27.930 --> 28:34.350
Ket one, bra zero looks like this and here's ket one, bra one.

267
28:34.350 --> 28:41.250
What we see happening is that there is just a single one in a matrix that's otherwise all zeros, and the position of that one

268
28:41.250 --> 28:47.190
is determined by which
classical states we choose in the bra and the ket.

269
28:47.190 --> 28:56.400
More precisely, and
this is true in general, for any choice of a classical state set, the matrix that we get by
multiplying ket a to bra b

270
28:56.400 --> 29:02.730
is the matrix with a one in the a, b entry and a zero for all other entries.

271
29:02.730 --> 29:10.920
And now that we have both the
first and the second parts of the Dirac notation, we have a very handy tool for connecting operations with matrices.

272
29:10.920 --> 29:17.130
So let's go back briefly
to deterministic operations and recall that a bit
earlier in the lesson,

273
29:17.130 --> 29:25.380
it was stated that for every function f of
this form right here, we have a deterministic operation that transforms a into f of a

274
29:25.380 --> 29:34.290
for each possible classical state a. And we said that for
any function like this, there's always a unique
matrix M that acts like this

275
29:34.290 --> 29:37.350
on standard basis states.

276
29:37.350 --> 29:43.920
Using the Dirac notation, we can now very easily express this matrix like you see right here,

277
29:43.920 --> 29:50.940
and we can see how sometimes
it's possible to work with matrices entirely
within the framework of the Dirac notation

278
29:50.940 --> 29:56.850
without ever explicitly converting
to vectors and matrices, meaning rectangles filled with numbers.

279
29:56.850 --> 30:04.350
In this case, we can check that the
required formula is true by multiplying M to ket a.

280
30:04.350 --> 30:14.730
We substitute our
expression for M like this and we can remove the parenthesis and snap together the bra
b with a ket a like this.

281
30:14.730 --> 30:23.400
And that's because matrix
multiplication is linear, in this case, in the first argument and it's associated so we can remove the parentheses.

282
30:23.400 --> 30:31.560
And now, recalling that we have a fixed a that we're talking about as we sum over all of the
possible choices of b,

283
30:31.560 --> 30:39.270
this bracket right here is
always gonna be equal to zero when b is not equal to a, so there won't be any
contribution to the sum,

284
30:39.270 --> 30:47.340
and when b is equal to a, the bracket will be equal to one and so we'll be left with
this one term right here.

285
30:47.340 --> 30:54.690
That's the formula we wanted and so we have a very nice and simple way of expressing a function as a matrix.

286
30:54.690 --> 31:03.510
In addition to deterministic operations, we also have operations that
themselves introduce randomness or uncertainty about the
classical state of a system.

287
31:03.510 --> 31:11.010
We use the term probabilistic operation to mean operations like this, and to be precise, when we say probabilistic operation,

288
31:11.010 --> 31:18.600
we mean operations that
might introduce randomness, so deterministic operations are actually a special case
of probabilistic operations

289
31:18.600 --> 31:22.260
that just don't happen to
introduce any randomness.

290
31:22.260 --> 31:26.280
Here's a simple example where
some randomness is introduced.

291
31:26.280 --> 31:32.340
This is an operation on a single bit. The way that it works is that if the classical state
of the bit is a zero,

292
31:32.340 --> 31:39.750
then nothing happens. The bit stays as a zero, but if the classical
state of the bit is a one, then the operation flips the bit to zero

293
31:39.750 --> 31:43.200
with probability equal to 1/2.

294
31:43.200 --> 31:46.230
There's no special name
for this operation, at least not that I'm aware of.

295
31:46.230 --> 31:52.050
It's just an example, but you could imagine performing
this operation on a bit.

296
31:52.050 --> 31:59.280
Just like deterministic operations, probabilistic operations can
be represented by matrices and their actions on probabilistic states

297
31:59.280 --> 32:04.260
are given by matrix-vector multiplication just like before.

298
32:04.260 --> 32:11.520
This time, it's not necessarily the case that the matrices have exactly one, one in each column and zeros otherwise.

299
32:11.520 --> 32:16.560
Probabilistic operations are
more generally represented by stochastic matrices.

300
32:16.560 --> 32:23.760
These are matrices whose entries are all
non-negative real numbers and where the entries in
each column sum to one.

301
32:23.760 --> 32:30.240
That's equivalent to saying
that stochastic matrices are matrices where every column
forms a probability vector.

302
32:30.240 --> 32:35.250
That makes sense when you think about
the action of a matrix on a standard basis vector.

303
32:35.250 --> 32:42.870
You consider whatever
classical state you wish and you imagine dropping that state into the top of the matrix in whatever column corresponds
to that classical state,

304
32:42.870 --> 32:50.580
and that column tells you what
the probabilistic state is that comes out as a probability vector.

305
32:50.580 --> 32:56.280
The probabilistic operation
in our example, for instance, is described by this matrix right here.

306
32:56.280 --> 33:03.720
If we perform this operation
on the classical state zero, then the probabilistic state we get is given by the first column,

307
33:03.720 --> 33:11.730
which is, again, the classical state zero or equivalently, the probabilistic
state where zero occurs with probability one.

308
33:11.730 --> 33:20.700
If instead, we perform this operation on the classical state one, then we effectively just randomize the bit and correspondingly, we get
this probability vector here

309
33:20.700 --> 33:27.090
where the probability for
each of the possible states is equal to 1/2.

310
33:27.090 --> 33:34.500
In general, if we perform this operation on any probabilistic state, then the effect is essentially
just a weighted average between the two columns

311
33:34.500 --> 33:37.890
because that's how a matrix-vector
multiplication works.

312
33:37.890 --> 33:44.340
It's linear, so we just average the two
possible outcomes accordingly.

313
33:44.340 --> 33:51.540
When we think about probabilistic
operations in this way, it's natural to think about
them as potentially introducing or injecting randomness.

314
33:51.540 --> 33:58.800
We can just read the columns one by one and we can see the randomness
that they introduce for each possible classical state.

315
33:58.800 --> 34:07.530
You can also think about
probabilistic operations in a slightly different way, which is that they're random choices of deterministic operations.

316
34:07.530 --> 34:14.190
For instance, in our example, we can think about this operation as being equivalent to
flipping a fair coin

317
34:14.190 --> 34:20.910
and either performing the
constant zero function or the identity function
each with probability 1/2,

318
34:20.910 --> 34:24.300
and you can see that reflected
right here by this equation.

319
34:24.300 --> 34:29.340
That's always possible for
any probabilistic operation, and it's pretty intuitive.

320
34:29.340 --> 34:35.400
If you made random choices
as part of some process, you could always imagine making those random choices in advance

321
34:35.400 --> 34:41.430
and then hard coding those
choices into some collection of deterministic operations.

322
34:41.430 --> 34:50.220
It's sometimes quite helpful to think about probabilistic
operations in this way, and we'll see an example
of this down the road in a couple of lessons.

323
34:50.220 --> 34:59.910
The last thing to say
about classical information for this lesson concerns composing
probabilistic operations, which just means performing
one after the other.

324
34:59.910 --> 35:10.110
Let's suppose that we
have some system named X and M1 through Mn are stochastic matrices representing probabilistic
operations on X.

325
35:10.110 --> 35:17.280
Imagine first that we have
a probability vector v, which represents a probabilistic
state of X at some moment, and then we first apply

326
35:17.280 --> 35:23.940
the first probabilistic operation to X, which is represented by the matrix M1, and then we apply the second
probabilistic operation,

327
35:23.940 --> 35:27.000
which is represented by M2.

328
35:27.000 --> 35:33.600
If we do that, then the
probability vector we get after applying just the first
operation is M1 times v,

329
35:33.600 --> 35:41.190
and then when we apply
the second operation, the resulting probability vector is M2 multiplied to whatever vector we obtained

330
35:41.190 --> 35:45.870
after applying M1. So it looks like this.

331
35:45.870 --> 35:52.620
Now, matrix multiplication
is an associative operation, which means that it doesn't matter where we put these parentheses.

332
35:52.620 --> 35:56.760
So we could just as easily
put the parentheses like this.

333
35:56.760 --> 36:03.690
That's very simple, but it's also interesting because it reveals that we
can think about the operation where we first apply M1

334
36:03.690 --> 36:08.280
and then we apply M2
as a single operation.

335
36:08.280 --> 36:17.970
In other words, the
probabilistic operation we get by composing the first and
second probabilistic operation is represented by the
matrix product, M2 times M1,

336
36:17.970 --> 36:22.140
and that's the same operation regardless of what probabilistic
state we started with.

337
36:22.140 --> 36:29.070
We don't need to know anything about the probability vector v to think about or to describe
this composed operation.

338
36:29.070 --> 36:35.550
Notice that the order
here is M2 on the left and M1 on the right, which is because the
matrix on the right, M1,

339
36:35.550 --> 36:43.830
is the one that gets
multiplied to the vector v, whereas M2 gets multiplied
to whatever vector we get after multiplying by M1.

340
36:43.830 --> 36:49.230
So we always have to keep in mind that the order in some
sense gets reversed.

341
36:49.230 --> 36:57.360
The operation performed
first is the one on the right and the operation that gets performed last or in this case, second,
is the one on the left.

342
36:57.360 --> 37:04.290
If we don't stop with the second operation and we apply all of them in
order starting with the first and ending with the last one, which is Mn,

343
37:04.290 --> 37:11.040
then the composition of all
of these operations together is given by this product
that you see right here,

344
37:11.040 --> 37:17.010
and you see that the ordering
once again is reversed for exactly the same reason as before.

345
37:17.010 --> 37:23.700
So in short, compositions
of probabilistic operations are represented by products
of stochastic matrices that represent them.

346
37:23.700 --> 37:28.560
Keeping in mind that this is
the ordering of the matrices in the product.

347
37:28.560 --> 37:34.590
You will always get a stochastic matrix by taking a product of
stochastic matrices like this, and sometimes we express this fact

348
37:34.590 --> 37:43.140
by saying that the stochastic
matrices are closed under multiplication, and the way that you
can think about this is that you can't get out of the
set of stochastic matrices

349
37:43.140 --> 37:47.340
by multiplying them because the set is closed.

350
37:47.340 --> 37:52.770
Getting back to the
ordering of the matrices in this product, it's important to note that the
ordering really does matter.

351
37:52.770 --> 38:00.030
Matrix multiplication is not commutative. If you change the ordering of
the matrices in the product, you might change the result,

352
38:00.030 --> 38:05.940
and we don't need to look any further than the deterministic
operations to see this.

353
38:05.940 --> 38:14.782
Here's a simple example of
two stochastic matrices, both of which represent
deterministic operations where the ordering matters.

354
38:14.782 --> 38:23.370
M1 represents the constant zero function. Assuming, we're imagining that these two operations are on bits, just like in the example from earlier.

355
38:23.370 --> 38:29.700
M2 represents the not
operation or a bit flip.

356
38:29.700 --> 38:37.920
If you perform M1 first
and then you perform M2, the result is this matrix right here, which represents the
constant one function.

357
38:37.920 --> 38:43.950
If you set a bit to zero
and then you flip it, it's the same thing as just
setting that bit to one.

358
38:43.950 --> 38:50.400
On the other hand, if you perform M2 first
and then you perform M1, this is the result right here,

359
38:50.400 --> 38:55.650
and this makes sense because if you flip a bit
and then you set it to zero, it's the same thing as
just setting it to zero.

360
38:55.650 --> 39:03.150
It didn't matter that you flipped it. Obviously, these two
matrices are not the same, and so we have a very
simple example revealing

361
39:03.150 --> 39:07.110
that the order does matter. Of course, this is not surprising at all.

362
39:07.110 --> 39:12.150
We all know that the order in which
operations are performed matters or at least, it can matter.

363
39:12.150 --> 39:18.240
For example, if you light a
match and then you blow on it, the result is very different
from blowing on the match first

364
39:18.240 --> 39:27.690
and then lighting it. At this point, we've talked quite a lot
about classical information and now it's finally time to
discuss quantum information.

365
39:27.690 --> 39:37.080
And what we'll find is that
mathematically speaking, quantum information works
in a very similar way to classical information
with some key differences.

366
39:37.080 --> 39:44.400
The first key difference
is right at the start, how we define a state, in this case, a quantum state of a system,

367
39:44.400 --> 39:53.820
and there is a sense in which this one choice how
we define a quantum state largely determines how
quantum information works.

368
39:53.820 --> 40:03.510
We'll also define how
measurements and operations work, and in the next lesson, we'll discuss how
quantum information works not just for single systems
but for multiple systems,

369
40:03.510 --> 40:11.820
but these things actually
follow pretty naturally once the notion of a quantum state of a single system in
isolation has been established.

370
40:11.820 --> 40:18.660
Here's the definition. A quantum state of a system is represented by a column vector whose indices are placed

371
40:18.660 --> 40:22.170
in correspondence with the
classical states of that system.

372
40:22.170 --> 40:29.130
So we're assuming here that
the system we're talking about has some set of classical states, just like when we talked
about classical information

373
40:29.130 --> 40:36.810
and probabilistic states. The entries in a quantum state
vector are complex numbers as opposed to the probabilistic case

374
40:36.810 --> 40:40.020
where the entries are
non-negative real numbers.

375
40:40.020 --> 40:47.070
And this time, the sum of the absolute
values squared of the entries must equal one as opposed to the sum being equal to one

376
40:47.070 --> 40:50.610
as we have in the probabilistic case.

377
40:50.610 --> 40:57.660
The complex numbers that appear
in a quantum state vector are sometimes called amplitudes and they play a role that's
similar to probabilities,

378
40:57.660 --> 41:03.660
but they aren't probabilities and they don't have the
same interpretation.

379
41:03.660 --> 41:10.530
Now, I can't give you a good reason for why quantum states
should be defined like this other than to say that
physicists have discovered

380
41:10.530 --> 41:18.390
that this definition
is physically relevant and it allows us to describe and model
quantum mechanical systems.

381
41:18.390 --> 41:29.010
In other words, we choose this definition
because it works, not because there are
any particular reasons why quantum states should
be defined like this.

382
41:29.010 --> 41:36.420
With respect to the
mathematics of this notion of a quantum state, the first step towards understanding it and working with it is
to recall this definition

383
41:36.420 --> 41:43.680
for the Euclidean norm of a vector, which you can think of geometrically as the length of a vector, just like you would think about the length

384
41:43.680 --> 41:52.080
of a two-dimensional real vector if you drew it on a piece
of paper as an arrow starting from the origin in the usual way.

385
41:52.080 --> 42:00.060
Specifically, if we have a
column vector v like this, which we assume has
complex number entries, alpha one through alpha n,

386
42:00.060 --> 42:05.250
then the Euclidean norm of v is defined like you see right here.

387
42:05.250 --> 42:11.280
This is the notation we
use for the Euclidean norm putting these double bars around whatever vector we're talking about.

388
42:11.280 --> 42:17.550
In this case, it's v, and the way the Euclidean norm is defined is that it's the square root of the sum

389
42:17.550 --> 42:22.500
of the absolute values squared
of the entries of the vector.

390
42:22.500 --> 42:30.720
So another way to define what
a quantum state vector is is that a quantum state vector is a column vector having
complex number entries

391
42:30.720 --> 42:38.940
whose Euclidean norm is equal to one, which is to say that it's a unit vector with respect to the Euclidean norm.

392
42:38.940 --> 42:44.280
That's because the sum of
the absolute value squared is equal to one if and only if the Euclidean
norm is equal to one.

393
42:44.280 --> 42:50.880
The square root doesn't change anything when the sum of the absolute
values squared is equal to one.

394
42:50.880 --> 42:57.810
So that's what a quantum state vector is. It's a column vector with indices that correspond to the
classical states of a system

395
42:57.810 --> 43:03.090
having complex number entries and Euclidean norm equal to one.

396
43:03.090 --> 43:10.260
What that means or what it implies or how we should interpret this
notion is a different matter and in some sense,

397
43:10.260 --> 43:18.570
the study of quantum
information and computation is an exploration of what
this definition implies, at least, in terms of
information processing.

398
43:18.570 --> 43:22.470
This is simply the starting point.

399
43:22.470 --> 43:29.970
As an aside, let me mention that there
are other so-called norms besides the Euclidean norm and this notation right
here with the double bars

400
43:29.970 --> 43:33.360
around a vector doesn't always
mean the Euclidean norm.

401
43:33.360 --> 43:38.400
In different contexts, this notation could refer
to a different norm.

402
43:38.400 --> 43:44.400
For example, the sum
of the absolute values with no squares or square
root is a different norm,

403
43:44.400 --> 43:50.520
often called the one norm. There are quite a lot of
different norms, in fact.

404
43:50.520 --> 43:58.440
Sometimes you'll see
this notation being used with a subscript after
the second set of bars that provides more information about what norm we're talking about.

405
43:58.440 --> 44:05.280
And when we do that, it's pretty typical that the number two as a subscript
means the Euclidean norm.

406
44:05.280 --> 44:11.310
But in this series, whenever we have a
column vector like this, this double bar notation all by itself

407
44:11.310 --> 44:14.940
means the Euclidean norm.

408
44:14.940 --> 44:21.030
Here are a few examples
of quantum state vectors and these particular quantum state vectors are qubit state vectors,

409
44:21.030 --> 44:26.520
which means that the
classical states of our system are zero and one.

410
44:26.520 --> 44:34.230
The word qubit is short for quantum bit, which is really just a bit
that can be in a quantum state.

411
44:34.230 --> 44:42.240
The first two examples are really simple. The standard basis vectors
ket zero and ket one are quantum state vectors.

412
44:42.240 --> 44:51.180
They're both column vectors, and the indices correspond
to the classical states is zero and one, and the entries of these
vectors are complex numbers.

413
44:51.180 --> 44:58.170
For these particular vectors, the entries are zero and one, which are real numbers, and in fact, they're integers, but they're also complex numbers

414
44:58.170 --> 45:02.970
that happen to have
imaginary part equal to zero.

415
45:02.970 --> 45:06.360
Each vector has one entry equal to one and one entry equal to zero.

416
45:06.360 --> 45:11.730
So when we sum the absolute
values of the entries, we get one in both cases.

417
45:11.730 --> 45:19.380
So the conditions
required for these vectors to be quantum state vectors are satisfied.

418
45:19.380 --> 45:25.680
The next two examples are very commonly encountered qubit states called the plus state and the minus state.

419
45:25.680 --> 45:34.230
They're denoted as you
see here on the screen, either with a ket plus
or a ket minus like this, and they're defined as
you can see right here.

420
45:34.230 --> 45:41.340
Again, the entries of these
vectors are complex numbers. This time, they're either positive one over square root of two or negative one over square root of two,

421
45:41.340 --> 45:47.520
and when we sum the
absolute values squared, we get 1/2 plus 1/2, which is one.

422
45:47.520 --> 45:55.380
By the way, putting a
plus sign or a minus sign inside of a ket like this
might seem a little strange because these aren't classical
states of our system,

423
45:55.380 --> 46:00.480
but this notation is used nevertheless, and we'll come back to this momentarily.

424
46:00.480 --> 46:06.900
But for now, in short, we can use the Dirac notation to put whatever name we want for a vector inside of a ket.

425
46:06.900 --> 46:13.710
The vector doesn't have to
be a standard basis vector when we use the Dirac notation.

426
46:13.710 --> 46:16.770
Here's a final qubit state
example for the moment, anyway.

427
46:16.770 --> 46:23.490
It's a quantum state vector of a qubit that doesn't have a special name, and it's not particularly significant.

428
46:23.490 --> 46:29.100
The entries of this vector are one plus two times i
over three and negative 2/3.

429
46:29.100 --> 46:35.970
These are complex numbers, and if you compute the
absolute values squared of these two entries, you'll get 5/9 for the first one

430
46:35.970 --> 46:44.520
and 4/9 for the second one. So the sum of the absolute
value squared is equal to one.

431
46:44.520 --> 46:50.820
And here's one last example. This time for a system
whose classical states are the four card suits.

432
46:50.820 --> 46:58.110
I don't know why we would have a system whose classical states
are the four card suits being in a quantum state, but it is possible in principle

433
46:58.110 --> 47:01.920
and it's just meant as an example.

434
47:01.920 --> 47:08.490
The entries corresponding
to the different suits are 1/2 for clubs, negative
i over two for diamonds,

435
47:08.490 --> 47:14.580
zero for hearts because it doesn't appear in the sum and one over square
root of two for spades.

436
47:14.580 --> 47:21.060
And here's what it looks
like as a column vector, assuming that we've ordered
the classical states as we did before,

437
47:21.060 --> 47:24.450
which is the order that
you see right here.

438
47:24.450 --> 47:30.120
Taking the absolute value
squared of these entries gives one quarter for the first one, also one quarter for the next one.

439
47:30.120 --> 47:34.710
The absolute value squared
of zero is equal to zero, so that entry doesn't
contribute to the sum.

440
47:34.710 --> 47:44.010
And finally, for the last one, we get 1/2. So the sum is equal to one as is required for this vector
to be a quantum state vector.

441
47:44.010 --> 47:51.930
Now just a moment ago, we used the notation
ket plus and ket minus to referred to two qubit state vectors that aren't standard basis vectors.

442
47:51.930 --> 48:01.200
And I'd like to return
to this point briefly and explain how the Dirac notation is used for arbitrary vectors and not just for standard basis vectors.

443
48:01.200 --> 48:07.440
As I've already mentioned, we can use whatever name we
want inside of a bra or ket to refer to a vector.

444
48:07.440 --> 48:12.390
Kets are column vectors
and bras are row vectors just like before.

445
48:12.390 --> 48:18.930
As an example, the Greek letter
psi is very commonly used inside of a ket to refer to some arbitrary vector,

446
48:18.930 --> 48:25.500
and here, we're using it to
give a name to the state vector from before that doesn't
have a special name.

447
48:25.500 --> 48:29.363
When we do this, the let our psi doesn't
necessarily have any meaning all by itself.

448
48:29.363 --> 48:36.120
It's just the name of a vector, and it's inside of a ket to help us to clarify
that it's a column vector.

449
48:36.120 --> 48:42.240
This can be a little
bit confusing sometimes, and there is a potential for ambiguity if the letter psi could be associated

450
48:42.240 --> 48:50.700
with a classical state of
some system for instance, but it generally doesn't
cause any problems, and you don't have to use
the Dirac notation like this

451
48:50.700 --> 48:58.200
if you don't want to. Using a lower case letter such
as u, v, or w without a ket is also a fine way to
denote a column vector

452
48:58.200 --> 49:01.530
or more specifically,
a quantum state vector.

453
49:01.530 --> 49:05.610
It's your choice what notation
you use to express yourself.

454
49:05.610 --> 49:10.590
You just need to make
sure that number one, the meaning of what you
are trying to express is clear to others.

455
49:10.590 --> 49:18.810
And number two, that you understand what
others are trying to express even when their preferences for notation aren't the same as yours.

456
49:18.810 --> 49:24.960
There is one very important rule for using the Dirac notation
for arbitrary vectors and that is that if you
have a column vector

457
49:24.960 --> 49:31.320
that you've decided to write
as ket psi, for instance, or it could be a different
name inside of a ket, then the row vector bra psi

458
49:31.320 --> 49:35.040
is understood to be
the conjugate transpose of the vector ket psi.

459
49:35.040 --> 49:42.000
And here, this is written as an equation where this dagger right here refers to the conjugate transpose.

460
49:42.000 --> 49:49.950
What that is specifically is
the row vector you get by, number one, transposing the vector, meaning that you flip
the vector on its side and you change it from a column into a row

461
49:49.950 --> 49:56.220
without actually changing the entries. And number two, taking the complex conjugate
of each of the entries.

462
49:56.220 --> 50:04.080
You can actually perform
those two operations, the transpose and the
entry-wise complex conjugate in either order or those
two operations commute.

463
50:04.080 --> 50:13.020
So for the vector in this example, given that we've decided to
call this vector ket psi, it's understood that bra psi
means this vector right here

464
50:13.020 --> 50:20.850
where we've transposed the vector by turning ket zero and ket
one into bra zero and bra one, and we've taken the complex
conjugate of each entry,

465
50:20.850 --> 50:28.350
which is why one plus
two times i over three turns into one minus two
times i over three right here.

466
50:28.350 --> 50:33.360
Here's what these vectors look like when they're written
explicitly as a column vector and a row vector.

467
50:33.360 --> 50:40.770
Notice, by the way, that
this rule is consistent with the notation we use when we have classical states
inside of the bra and the ket.

468
50:40.770 --> 50:49.050
In that case, the entries are
all zero except for one, one, and so taking the complex
conjugate doesn't do anything in that case.

469
50:49.050 --> 50:56.130
We've now seen how quantum states are represented as vectors, but it's not clear at this
point what the meaning or the implications are

470
50:56.130 --> 51:01.680
in terms of what you
can do with the system in a quantum state or how you can interact with it.

471
51:01.680 --> 51:07.470
The first thing we need to do to bring these issues into focus
is to discuss measurements.

472
51:07.470 --> 51:14.610
Intuitively speaking,
measurements provide a mechanism for extracting classical
information from quantum systems.

473
51:14.610 --> 51:21.120
When we look at a system
when it's in a quantum state, we don't see a quantum state just like we don't see
probabilistic states,

474
51:21.120 --> 51:27.570
we see classical states, and this notion of a measurement is what provides the interface.

475
51:27.570 --> 51:34.710
If we, as humans, want to know something about a quantum system, we have to measure it, and in doing so, we'll extract classical information

476
51:34.710 --> 51:39.090
about whatever quantum
state that system was in.

477
51:39.090 --> 51:46.350
There are different
notions of measurements. The difference is one
of generality really, and we're going to start with the simplest and most basic one,

478
51:46.350 --> 51:50.370
which is typically called a
standard basis measurement.

479
51:50.370 --> 51:58.320
We will generalize this
in subsequent lessons. We'll talk about so-called
projective measurements in lesson three, and then later on in the
third unit of the series,

480
51:58.320 --> 52:05.580
we'll talk about general measurements, which are also called positive
operator valued measures or POVMs for short.

481
52:05.580 --> 52:10.860
But for now, we'll restrict our attention to standard basis measurements.

482
52:10.860 --> 52:18.000
When a measurement is
performed on a system, there will be some set
of possible outcomes of that measurement, which are classical outcomes,

483
52:18.000 --> 52:25.710
and in the case of a
standard basis measurement, those possible outcomes are
precisely the classical states of whatever system is being measured.

484
52:25.710 --> 52:32.280
Each of those classical states will be the outcome of the measurement with some probability, and that probability is
the absolute value squared

485
52:32.280 --> 52:41.220
of the entry corresponding
to that classical state of whatever quantum state
vector the system was in immediately prior to being measured.

486
52:41.220 --> 52:47.910
We know that the absolute value squared of any complex number is a non-negative real number, and we know from the definition
of quantum state vectors

487
52:47.910 --> 52:53.070
that the sum of the absolute
value squared of the entries of a quantum state vector is equal to one.

488
52:53.070 --> 53:01.350
So this makes sense. Each classical state will appear as the outcome of the
measurement with some probability and the probabilities sum to one.

489
53:01.350 --> 53:07.230
Here are a few examples. First, suppose we have a
qubit in the plus state.

490
53:07.230 --> 53:14.160
If we measure this qubit with respect to a standard
basis measurement, we get either a zero or
a one as the outcome.

491
53:14.160 --> 53:22.050
The probability of getting a zero is the absolute value
squared of one over root two, which is 1/2, and that's the same
probability of getting a one.

492
53:22.050 --> 53:27.630
So if you measure a plus state, you'll get a uniform random bit.

493
53:27.630 --> 53:32.820
If the system is in a minus
state rather than a plus state, then measuring works in
exactly the same way.

494
53:32.820 --> 53:36.780
The probabilities are, again, 1/2 for each possible outcome.

495
53:36.780 --> 53:44.340
The only difference here is that the plus sign turned into a minus sign, but when we take the absolute
value, nothing changes.

496
53:44.340 --> 53:53.310
If we measure this qubit state, the probability to get the outcome zero is the absolute value squared of one plus two times i
over three, which is 5/9,

497
53:53.310 --> 54:00.810
and the probability to get the outcome one is the absolute value squared
of negative 2/3, which is 4/9.

498
54:00.810 --> 54:07.830
And finally, measuring
the standard basis state, ket zero gives the outcome
zero with certainty, and likewise, measuring the state ket one

499
54:07.830 --> 54:14.250
yields the outcome one with certainty. That's because the absolute
value squared of one is one.

500
54:14.250 --> 54:22.710
Similar to what we had in
the probabilistic setting. We can associate these quantum
states, ket zero in ket one, with the system being in
those classical states,

501
54:22.710 --> 54:26.970
and this example is consistent
with that interpretation.

502
54:26.970 --> 54:33.120
Now, just like we had in
the probabilistic setting, if we measure a system when
it's in a quantum state,

503
54:33.120 --> 54:38.700
then the state will change, in general, as a result of having
performed that measurement.

504
54:38.700 --> 54:43.110
In particular, and again, this is exactly like we had
in the probabilistic setting.

505
54:43.110 --> 54:51.180
If we measure a system and the outcome of the measurement
is the classical state a, then the new quantum state
of the system becomes ket a.

506
54:51.180 --> 54:58.440
So for this state right
here, for instance, we see the same kind
of behavior that we had in the probabilistic setting.

507
54:58.440 --> 55:05.280
If we measure then with probability 5/9, we obtain the outcome zero, in which case, the state
transitions to ket zero,

508
55:05.280 --> 55:11.460
and with probability
4/9, the outcome is one, and the state transitions to ket one.

509
55:11.460 --> 55:17.460
Sometimes this phenomenon is referred to as a collapse
of the quantum state, and it's the kind of
thing that keeps people

510
55:17.460 --> 55:21.060
that study the foundations
of quantum mechanics awake at night.

511
55:21.060 --> 55:29.550
But from a purely
mathematical perspective, it's really quite simple
and very much analogous to what we have in the probabilistic case.

512
55:29.550 --> 55:35.910
The source of tension here, in some sense, concerns the fundamental
nature of quantum states and what they represent
and how they differ

513
55:35.910 --> 55:42.480
from probabilistic states. But at a mathematical level, this is perhaps what you might expect.

514
55:42.480 --> 55:48.690
Notice, by the way, that if
you measured a second time, then you would get exactly
the same result as you did for the first measurement.

515
55:48.690 --> 55:55.050
So there's a limit on how
much classical information can be extracted from a quantum state, and we'll come back to this point soon

516
55:55.050 --> 56:03.000
in another lesson. We've talked about quantum states as well as measurements, specifically standard basis measurements,

517
56:03.000 --> 56:08.610
which provide a way to
extract classical information from quantum states.

518
56:08.610 --> 56:16.680
The remaining topic for
this lesson is operations, specifically unitary operations, which describe how
quantum states of systems

519
56:16.680 --> 56:25.710
can be changed. Naturally, given that quantum
state vectors are different from probability vectors, you would expect that set
of allowable operations

520
56:25.710 --> 56:32.640
on quantum states is different than what we have for
classical information, and indeed, that's the case.

521
56:32.640 --> 56:39.510
Whereas operations on probabilistic states are represented by stochastic matrices, operations on quantum state vectors

522
56:39.510 --> 56:43.080
are represented by unitary matrices.

523
56:43.080 --> 56:47.336
Here's the definition of unitary matrices.

524
56:47.336 --> 56:55.020
A square matrix U having complex
number entries is unitary if it satisfies the equalities
that you see right here.

525
56:55.020 --> 57:02.700
The dagger represents
the conjugate transpose, which we already saw for vectors when we talked about the Dirac
notation a few moments ago.

526
57:02.700 --> 57:10.140
Here we're performing the
conjugate transpose on a matrix rather than a vector, but it's essentially the same thing.

527
57:10.140 --> 57:17.610
We transpose the matrix, which just means that we
swap rows and columns, so the JK entry becomes the KJ entry,

528
57:17.610 --> 57:21.870
and also we take the complex
conjugate of each entry.

529
57:21.870 --> 57:26.580
Also, this notation right here
means the identity matrix.

530
57:26.580 --> 57:32.760
These two equalities right
here are actually equivalent. If you have one, then you
automatically have the other.

531
57:32.760 --> 57:39.720
They're both equivalent to
saying that you is invertible, and the inverse is equal
to the conjugate transpose.

532
57:39.720 --> 57:46.380
That's only true for square
matrices, by the way. If you have a matrix that isn't square, then one of those two
equalities might be true,

533
57:46.380 --> 57:49.530
but then the other one won't be true.

534
57:49.530 --> 57:53.070
But here, we're talking
about square matrices.

535
57:53.070 --> 57:59.430
So this is the standard
definition for unitary matrices, and it's nice because it's easy to check
if a matrix is unitary.

536
57:59.430 --> 58:08.010
You just multiply the matrix to its conjugate transpose on either side, and you see if you get
the identity matrix.

537
58:08.010 --> 58:16.410
There's an equivalent way to characterize unitarian matrices, and that is that a
square matrix is unitary if and only if it never
changes the Euclidean norm

538
58:16.410 --> 58:24.690
of any vector when you multiply. An N by N matrix U is unitary if and only if the
Euclidean norm of U times v

539
58:24.690 --> 58:31.230
is equal to the Euclidean norm v for every n-dimensional column vector v with complex number entries.

540
58:31.230 --> 58:38.580
And therefore, if v is
a quantum state vector, then U times v is also
a quantum state vector because quantum state vectors

541
58:38.580 --> 58:43.140
are simply the vectors having
Euclidean norm equal to one.

542
58:43.140 --> 58:50.340
In fact, we can say a little bit more, which is that the unitary matrices are precisely the matrices that always transform
quantum state vectors

543
58:50.340 --> 58:56.670
into quantum state vectors. That's a similar situation to what we have for stochastic matrices
and probability vectors.

544
58:56.670 --> 59:04.110
The stochastic matrices
are precisely the matrices that always transform probability vectors into probability vectors.

545
59:04.110 --> 59:11.550
So once we've decided that operations should be represented by matrices, which is the same as saying that transformations act linearly

546
59:11.550 --> 59:21.030
on vectors representing states, these choices for the sets
of allowable operations follow naturally, at least,
in a mathematical sense.

547
59:21.030 --> 59:25.320
Now let's take a look at some examples of qubit unitary operations.

548
59:25.320 --> 59:31.950
We'll see many more examples
of unitary operations in subsequent lessons, including unitary operations and systems

549
59:31.950 --> 59:39.120
having more than two classical states. But for now, we'll focus just
on qubit unitary operations.

550
59:39.120 --> 59:46.950
We're going to be seeing these
particular examples arising again and again, so it's definitely worth getting
to know these operations.

551
59:46.950 --> 59:50.640
The first collection of examples are the so-called Pauli operations.

552
59:50.640 --> 59:56.130
These are the operations that correspond to the Pauli matrices, which are shown here.

553
59:56.130 --> 60:02.850
They're all unitary, and you can check that for each one according to the definition from before.

554
60:02.850 --> 60:10.350
These particular matrices
happen to be equal to their own conjugate transposes, which is to say that they're
all Hermitian matrices.

555
60:10.350 --> 60:19.320
So checking that they're
all unitary, in this case, is a matter of squaring each one and seeing that the result
is the identity matrix.

556
60:19.320 --> 60:28.980
The names you see for these
matrices are pretty standard, and you'll also see sigma
x, sigma y, and sigma z called simply X, Y, and Z.

557
60:28.980 --> 60:36.480
Do be aware, though, that the
capital letters X, Y, and Z are also commonly used for other purposes, even in the context of
quantum information,

558
60:36.480 --> 60:40.800
but they are very common
names for these matrices.

559
60:40.800 --> 60:48.210
The sigma x or X operation
is also called a bit flip or a not operation, which we've already seen
in the classical context.

560
60:48.210 --> 60:52.830
And the sigma z or Z operation
is also called a phase flip.

561
60:52.830 --> 61:00.960
And here, you can see the
action of these operations on the standard basis factors, which kind of explains
where these names come from.

562
61:00.960 --> 61:05.760
Certainly, it makes sense to
refer to sigma x as a bit flip based on this action right here.

563
61:05.760 --> 61:10.680
It simply flips the bit from
zero to one or one to zero.

564
61:10.680 --> 61:15.480
It also makes sense to
call sigma z a phase flip based on this action right here.

565
61:15.480 --> 61:18.660
But if that's not crystal clear
at the moment, that's okay.

566
61:18.660 --> 61:26.340
We'll encounter this
operation over and over and the significance
of putting a minus sign in front of the ket one
basis vector and not ket zero

567
61:26.340 --> 61:30.210
and why that's called a phase flip will be more clear later on.

568
61:30.210 --> 61:39.000
The next example is
the Hadamard operation, which is represented by
this matrix right here, which is pretty much always named H.

569
61:39.000 --> 61:47.310
Checking that H is unitary is once again a
straightforward calculation, which if I step out of the way, you can see right here.

570
61:47.310 --> 61:50.340
Similar to the Pauli matrices, H is its own conjugate transpose.

571
61:50.340 --> 62:00.360
So we have this equality right here, and when we perform the multiplication, we get the identity matrix as is required.

572
62:00.360 --> 62:05.280
The third example is
really an entire class of unitary operations
known as phase operations.

573
62:05.280 --> 62:12.510
These are operations
represented by any matrix that takes this form
that you see right here where theta is any real number.

574
62:12.510 --> 62:18.720
So this entry right here will
always be some complex number on the unit circle.

575
62:18.720 --> 62:23.190
Matrices like this are always unitary, which I will leave to you to verify.

576
62:23.190 --> 62:29.940
This time, the conjugate transpose won't be equal to the original matrix unless this number here happens
to be a one or a minus one,

577
62:29.940 --> 62:36.120
in which case, we end up with
either the identity matrix or sigma z, which we've
already encountered.

578
62:36.120 --> 62:47.460
Specifically, transposition
won't do anything to this matrix, but taking the complex
conjugate of each entry changes this entry right here
to e to the minus i theta.

579
62:47.460 --> 62:52.890
These two particular operations right here are particularly important
examples of phase operations.

580
62:52.890 --> 62:57.810
For the first one, we take
theta to be pi over two, and we get this matrix right here.

581
62:57.810 --> 63:03.870
This is commonly called an
S operation or an S gate when we're talking about circuits, which we won't discuss in this lesson,

582
63:03.870 --> 63:07.530
but that's an important
topic that's coming up soon.

583
63:07.530 --> 63:11.400
The second one is this operation. It's a T operation or a T gate.

584
63:11.400 --> 63:20.880
And for this one, theta
is equal to pi over four. And so when we compute the exponential, we get this value right here, which is one plus i over
the square root of two.

585
63:20.880 --> 63:25.500
Here are just a few quick examples to see a couple of these
operations in action.

586
63:25.500 --> 63:30.630
Here's the action of
the Hadamard operation on ket zero and ket one.

587
63:30.630 --> 63:38.910
If we go through the
matrix-vector multiplication, we see that what we obtain are the plus state and the
minus state respectively.

588
63:38.910 --> 63:47.220
If we perform the Hadamard operation on the plus state and the
minus state, on the other hand, we get back to ket zero and ket one.

589
63:47.220 --> 63:52.200
So if we clean things up a little bit, we can see the action more clearly.

590
63:52.200 --> 64:01.170
The Hadamard operation
transforms back and forth between the zero state and the plus state and between the one state
and the minus state.

591
64:01.170 --> 64:09.810
Concerning these two equations right here, notice that this gives us a simple way to detect the difference between a plus state and a minus state.

592
64:09.810 --> 64:16.230
As we saw earlier in the lesson, if we measure a plus
state and a minus state with respect to the
standard basis measurement,

593
64:16.230 --> 64:22.260
we get a uniform random bit in both cases, which doesn't help us to
detect the difference.

594
64:22.260 --> 64:28.690
But if we perform a Hadamard
operation and then we measure, we'll see a zero if the
original state was a plus state

595
64:28.690 --> 64:32.250
and a one if the original
state was a minus state.

596
64:32.250 --> 64:38.730
So these two states are indeed different, and they can be discriminated
perfectly by the method that I just described,

597
64:38.730 --> 64:44.460
which is to first perform
a Hadamard operation and then to measure.

598
64:44.460 --> 64:52.260
Going back to the example of
a qubit state we saw before that isn't particularly special, we can see what the Hadamard
operation does to the state

599
64:52.260 --> 64:57.810
by converting to the forms
that you see right here and performing the multiplication.

600
64:57.810 --> 65:03.990
And here is the result
which we can convert back to the Dirac notation if we wish,

601
65:03.990 --> 65:07.260
and that's one way to compute
these sorts of actions.

602
65:07.260 --> 65:13.410
Here's another example that illustrates that you don't always
have to convert explicitly to a matrix vector form.

603
65:13.410 --> 65:18.780
You can also perform these
computations directly using the Dirac notation.

604
65:18.780 --> 65:25.470
This example concerns the T operation, and here it is right
here just for reference.

605
65:25.470 --> 65:30.240
This operation has this action right here on standard basis states.

606
65:30.240 --> 65:38.130
And if we want to compute
the action of the T operation on a plus state, for instance, we can start by expanding the
definition of the plus state

607
65:38.130 --> 65:43.590
and then use linearity
to express the result as you see right here.

608
65:43.590 --> 65:53.460
We can now just plug in
these expressions up here, do just a little bit of
simplification for the second term, and we obtain the result.

609
65:53.460 --> 66:00.870
If for whatever reason we'd like to apply a Hadamard
operation to the result, we can do a similar thing.

610
66:00.870 --> 66:07.620
First, we substitute the expression for T acting on the plus state and we use linearity like we did before.

611
66:07.620 --> 66:14.340
And now, if we substitute the
expressions we already have for the Hadamard operation
acting on ket zero and ket one,

612
66:14.340 --> 66:22.260
we obtain this. And now, we can expand the
plus state and the minus state to get this expression right here,

613
66:22.260 --> 66:27.870
which we can simplify just by adding, and here is the final result.

614
66:27.870 --> 66:34.980
There's nothing particularly
special about this example. It's just meant to
illustrate this alternative but equivalent way of
calculating the actions

615
66:34.980 --> 66:40.920
of these operations. You can use whichever
way is more convenient in the situation at hand.

616
66:40.920 --> 66:48.360
One final point about
unitary operations is that compositions of unitary
operations are represented by matrix multiplication

617
66:48.360 --> 66:55.320
just like in the probabilistic setting, i.e., you can compute the action of a sequence of unitary operations

618
66:55.320 --> 67:02.130
by simply multiplying
the matrices together. And what you'll get is
a single unitary matrix representing the combined action

619
67:02.130 --> 67:05.880
of the sequence of operations.

620
67:05.880 --> 67:13.260
Just like we had for stochastic matrices, the unitary matrices are
closed under multiplication, so you'll always get a unitary matrix

621
67:13.260 --> 67:17.070
when you compose unitary operations.

622
67:17.070 --> 67:20.070
You have to make sure
you multiply the matrices in the correct order.

623
67:20.070 --> 67:26.160
But the way it works is just like it was for
stochastic operations where the matrix for the
first operation you perform

624
67:26.160 --> 67:32.400
will always appear on the right-hand side
of the matrix product, and the last one will appear
on the left-hand side.

625
67:32.400 --> 67:41.280
So just like before, the order is reversed in the sense that you compose from right to left rather than left to right.

626
67:41.280 --> 67:48.810
Here's an interesting example that gives rise to an operation known as the square root of not operation.

627
67:48.810 --> 67:56.640
Suppose that we first
apply a Hadamard operation followed by an S operation, followed by another Hadamard operation.

628
67:56.640 --> 68:00.750
The combined action of
these three operations is described by this product.

629
68:00.750 --> 68:08.160
Here's the first Hadamard operation, here's the S operation, and here's the second Hadamard operation.

630
68:08.160 --> 68:14.310
If we perform the matrix multiplication, which isn't shown here explicitly, but you can do this for
yourself if you wish,

631
68:14.310 --> 68:20.880
the result is this matrix right here. It's a unitary matrix, and we can either check that directly

632
68:20.880 --> 68:25.650
or we can trust in the fact that the unitary matrices are
closed under multiplication.

633
68:25.650 --> 68:32.550
It has to be unitary because these three matrices are unitary as we've already seen.

634
68:32.550 --> 68:35.850
We don't have any particular
quantum state vector in mind here.

635
68:35.850 --> 68:44.580
We can imagine performing
this sequence of operations on any quantum state vector, and this matrix describes the action.

636
68:44.580 --> 68:51.360
The reason why this combined operation, meaning the one described
by this matrix right here is called a spirit of not operation,

637
68:51.360 --> 68:59.430
is that by performing it
twice, we get a not operation, or in other words, a
sigma x or an X operation.

638
68:59.430 --> 69:04.800
Performing the operation
twice is represented by squaring the matrix or
multiplying it to itself.

639
69:04.800 --> 69:09.570
And if you do this, you'll see that the result
is the Pauli x matrix.

640
69:09.570 --> 69:18.870
And that's kind of peculiar, and it gives you just a hint that you can do some interesting things with quantum information that you can't do with
classical information.

641
69:18.870 --> 69:26.790
There's no classical operation, meaning one represented
by a stochastic matrix that gives us a not operation
if we perform it twice.

642
69:26.790 --> 69:33.690
So it's a nice example that reveals that quantum operations
behave very differently from classical operations.

643
69:33.690 --> 69:41.250
And that's it for lesson one. In this lesson, we discussed how quantum information works for single systems in isolation,

644
69:41.250 --> 69:46.290
and in the next lesson, we'll talk about how
quantum information works for multiple systems.

645
69:46.290 --> 69:51.150
Thanks for watching. If you have any questions, feel free to leave them in
the comments section below.
